 theories they replaced.Originally published in 1975.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aDramaxHistory and criticism. 0aTragedyxHistory and criticism. 0aTragedy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh  aAbsalom.  aAct of Violence.  aAeschylus.  aAfterword.  aAhab.  aAnalogy.  aAnecdote.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAntinomy.  aAntithesis.  aApollonian and Dionysian.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aBoredom.  aBrute fact.  aClytemnestra.  aCounterculture.  aCriticism.  aD. H. Lawrence.  aDeal with the Devil.  aDialectic.  aDialectician.  aDichotomy.  aDie Welt.  aDionysian Mysteries.  aDithyramb.  aDudley Fitts.  aElectra complex.  aEmblem.  aEpic poetry.  aEquivalents.  aF. L. Lucas.  aFairy.  aFalsity.  aFaust.  aFiction.  aFrancis Fergusson.  aGenre.  aGeorge Steiner.  aGood and evil.  aGreek chorus.  aGreek mythology.  aGreek tragedy.  aHamartia.  aHedonism.  aHumour.  aHymn to Proserpine.  aHypocrisy.  aIdeology.  aIndividuation.  aIrony.  aIrresistible force paradox.  aJacques Derrida.  aLiterature.  aLong Day's Journey into Night.  aLurch (The Addams Family).  aLyric poetry.  aMichael Robartes and the Dancer.  aMoby-Dick.  aMonomania.  aMourning Becomes Electra.  aName-dropping.  aNihilis